19. P. Scipionem: i.e.‚ P. cornelius sulpio, to which the agnomen Africanus was added after his defeat of Hannibal. He conquered all Spain between 210 and 206. In 204 he went over to Africa from Sicily and won a great battle near Utica, which occasioned the recall of Hannibal.

22. impraesentiarum: an adverb equivalent to inpraesentia, p. 8, l. 6; a colloquial expression probably from in praesentiit rerum.

23. bellum componere: cf. bellum compositurum, p. 37, l. 20.

24. In conloquium convenit, etc. : a conference is agreed upon ; on terms they did reat agree (lit. terms did nat meet).

25. Post id factum: after this took place, lit. aster tais deed.

26. Zamam: this was southwest of Carthage. Itis thought that Naraggara, which lay fifty miles to the west of Zama, was the scene of the battle ; the armies had encamped there prior to the colloquy. Hadrumetum was not over one hundred miles from Zama, one hundred and fifty from Naraggara; hence the statement trecenta milia is an exaggeration.

Paper 71. abest ab Zama: abis used even with names of towns when the distance from one place to another is stated. 8. acerrime occupatus : most actively engaged.
